<UserControl x:Class="CapyBro.Controls.HelpIcon"
             xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
             x:Name="Root">

  <!--
    Small "?" affordance that surfaces a tooltip on hover.  Use next
    to section headings or fields whose meaning isn't immediately
    obvious to a first-time user (hotkey conflict rules, what an
    OpenRouter model id looks like, etc.).

    Why this control exists:
      • Tooltips on labels alone aren't *discoverable* — the user has
        to guess that hovering will reveal a hint.  A visible "?"
        glyph signals "more info available here" the same way every
        modern web app and OS settings page does.
      • Centralising the visual treatment (size, colour, hover
        affordance, hit area) means every help icon in the app
        looks identical and behaves the same way — no per-call
        styling drift.

    The actual hint copy comes from the bound HintText DP and
    renders via WPF's stock ToolTip pipeline, which our custom
    Themes/Tooltips.xaml restyles into the dark Surface-Layer-2
    multi-line popup automatically.  No special tooltip plumbing
    needed here.

    Hit area: 20×20 transparent Border so the cursor doesn't have
    to land precisely on a stroked pixel of the glyph for the
    tooltip / hover affordance to engage.  WCAG-recommended
    minimum click target is 24×24, but inline next to a heading
    we're sized to be visually present without being chunky;
    Cursor=Help (a "?" cursor) is the discoverability cue.

    Hover treatment: the Path's Stroke is bound through a Style
    DataTrigger that watches the Border's IsMouseOver via
    ElementName.  Stroke brightens from OnSurfaceMuted to
    OnSurfaceDefault when the cursor is over the hit area —
    Style Setters on a Path can't target other elements directly,
    so the only way to flip the stroke from a parent's hover
    state is to bind through a property trigger on the Path
    itself.  ElementName binding (rather than RelativeSource
    AncestorType=Border) is robust against the Path being moved
    inside additional wrappers in future tweaks.
  -->

  <Border x:Name="HitArea"
          Width="20"
          Height="20"
          Background="Transparent"
          Cursor="Help"
          ToolTip="{Binding HintText, ElementName=Root}"
          AutomationProperties.Name="{Binding HintText, ElementName=Root}"
          SnapsToDevicePixels="True">
    <Path Data="{StaticResource Icon.HelpCircle}"
          StrokeThickness="1.5"
          StrokeStartLineCap="Round"
          StrokeEndLineCap="Round"
          StrokeLineJoin="Round"
          Width="16"
          Height="16"
          Stretch="Uniform"
          HorizontalAlignment="Center"
          VerticalAlignment="Center">
      <Path.Style>
        <Style TargetType="Path">
          <Setter Property="Stroke" Value="{DynamicResource OnSurfaceMutedBrush}" />
          <Style.Triggers>
            <DataTrigger Binding="{Binding IsMouseOver, ElementName=HitArea}" Value="True">
              <Setter Property="Stroke" Value="{DynamicResource OnSurfaceDefaultBrush}" />
            </DataTrigger>
          </Style.Triggers>
        </Style>
      </Path.Style>
    </Path>
  </Border>
</UserControl>
